---
import VizPlaceholder from '../VizPlaceholder.astro';
---

<section id="harness-vs-meta" class="px-6 py-20 md:py-28">
  <div class="mx-auto max-w-3xl">
    <p class="font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.25em] text-accent">
      The distinction
    </p>
    <h2
      class="mt-4 text-3xl font-semibold tracking-tight text-neutral-50 sm:text-4xl"
    >
      Harness vs meta-harness
    </h2>
    <p class="mt-6 text-lg text-neutral-400">
      You can't define "meta" without the base.
    </p>
    <p class="mt-6 text-xl font-medium text-neutral-200">
      A harness runs one loop over one environment. A meta-harness operates
      above one or more harnesses, handling what spans loops, repos, and time.
    </p>

    <div class="mt-10 space-y-10">
      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-100">Next.js to React</h3>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
          Next.js didn't replace React. It added the pieces that make building
          React apps in production easier: routing, server-side rendering, and
          more. Some of what a meta-harness adds will get absorbed into the
          harnesses beneath it, but most won't. Next.js is React with the
          annoying parts solved.
          <mark>A meta-harness is your harness with the annoying parts solved.</mark>
        </p>
      </div>

      <div>
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-neutral-100">
          Kubernetes for agents
        </h3>
        <p class="mt-3 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-300">
          The model is the service inside the container. The harness is the
          container. The meta-harness is Kubernetes. A container runs one
          service in isolation. Kubernetes doesn't replace the container. It
          schedules many of them, gives them a shared network, and keeps state
          that outlives any single one. A meta-harness does the same for
          harnesses.
        </p>
        <p class="mt-4 text-lg leading-relaxed text-neutral-400">
          But the "Kubernetes for agents" analogy only captures part of it. It
          misses continuity, collaboration, and other aspects that
          meta-harnesses add.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-14 max-w-5xl">
    <VizPlaceholder label="the signature diagram revisited, toggling between the Next.js and Kubernetes analogy overlays" />
  </div>

  <div class="mx-auto mt-6 max-w-5xl">
    <p class="text-sm text-neutral-500">
      Term coined at{' '}
      <a
        href="https://codepick.dev/en/guides/meta-harness-2026/"
        class="text-accent underline-offset-4 hover:underline"
        target="_blank"
        rel="noopener"
      >
        codepick.dev/en/guides/meta-harness-2026
      </a>.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
